# ADR-002: Hybrid, album-context-aware audio identification

## Status

Accepted (2026-07-14)

## Context

The original Phase 2 plan (see `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` §3 and `task.md`) assumed
a short (~10-15s) audio clip, fingerprinted with Chromaprint and looked up
against AcoustID, would be enough to identify whatever's currently playing.

Empirical testing on 2026-07-14 disproved that assumption. Using a clean
MP3 of a well-known track (Gorillaz - "Feel Good Inc.", not a mic recording,
so signal quality wasn't the variable) and sweeping clip length/offset:

- Clips under ~90 seconds returned **zero results** from AcoustID's lookup
  API in most cases, regardless of which part of the song was sampled.
- A full ~120s+ clip matched instantly at 0.97 confidence.
- The 30-90s range was inconsistent: sometimes a moderate-confidence match
  (0.68-0.83), sometimes nothing, with no clean monotonic curve.

Conclusion: **duration, not mic/room signal quality, is the dominant
bottleneck.** A naive "poll every N seconds with a short clip" loop is both
slow (has to wait ~90s+ per attempt to get a reliable answer) and unreliable
for the actual goal of promptly catching a track skip mid-album.

## Decision

Adopt a layered identification system instead of a single blind
fingerprint-and-poll loop, built around one new product constraint: **the
user selects which album is about to play, from their existing catalog,
before starting playback.** That turns "which of ~40 million recordings is
this" into "which of ~12 known tracks is this," which is a fundamentally
easier problem and is what makes the other layers viable.

The five layers, working together:

1. **Album pre-selection** — the user picks the active album via the web UI
   before playing it. The app fetches and stores that album's tracklist
   (title + duration per track) from MusicBrainz or Discogs release detail
   endpoints, since our existing barcode-search data is album-level only.
2. **Silence/gap detection** — continuous, cheap RMS-energy monitoring of
   the input stream detects the brief silence between tracks in near
   real time, independent of fingerprinting. This is what makes skip
   detection *responsive*: it tells us the instant something changed, so we
   know exactly when to re-identify instead of polling blindly.
3. **Track-order + duration timer** — once a track is confirmed, advance
   `now_playing` automatically after that track's known runtime elapses, at
   zero ongoing API cost. A gap firing earlier/later than the timer expects
   signals a skip and triggers re-identification.
4. **Album-constrained fuzzy matching** — the core identification technique.
   Capture a shorter clip (~30s) than a blind approach would trust, send it
   to AcoustID, and accept a lower-confidence result (down to ~0.4-0.5) if
   its title fuzzy-matches one of the active album's known tracks. This is
   sound specifically because the candidate set is small and known, per the
   test data above (moderate-confidence matches were sometimes exactly
   right).
5. **Local fingerprint caching (self-training)** — once a track is
   confirmed via (4), cache the fingerprint computed from *our own mic
   input* for that (album, track) pair. Future plays of the same physical
   disc through the same mic/room compare against this local cache first,
   avoiding AcoustID entirely on repeat listens and sidestepping the
   duration problem, since both sides of the comparison went through the
   same acoustic path.

Progressive/adaptive clip length (start at ~30s, extend to 60s/90s only if
no usable candidate comes back) is used within layer 4 as needed, rather
than always paying the longest-case latency.

## Consequences

- Requires a new `tracks` table (per-album track listing) and a local
  fingerprint cache, beyond the schema built in Phase 1.
- `listener.py` is meaningfully more complex than the original single
  capture-fingerprint-lookup loop implied.
- Adds a manual step for the user (selecting the album before playing) that
  the original design didn't require. This is a deliberate trade-off: it's
  what makes fast, reliable identification possible at all with clip
  lengths short enough to be responsive.
- The first play of any given album is still slower/less certain than
  repeat plays, since the local cache (layer 5) only helps once a track has
  been identified at least once.
- Still to validate: real CD player audio via line-in (not mic), and
  whether the ~30-90s duration finding generalizes across other tracks
  and not just this one test song.
